{
  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, currently, DL-based segmentation is often corrected by clinicians to ensure quality.",
    "Here, clinicians may prefer certain patterns in the model's segmentation behavior, for example over-segmentation rather than under-segmentation, as it may be easier to correct.",
    "These practical preferences are not captured by popular metrics of segmentation performance but may play an important role in clinical adoption 59.",
    "Another important aspect of the clinical application of deep-learning-based segmentation models is the quantification of segmentation uncertainty.",
    "This approach can help clinicians when they are manually revising model segmentations, as areas marked as uncertain are most likely to contain mistakes."
  ]
}